#LINEAR

svm_housing_linear <- svm(ownership ~ ., data = training_housing, 
                   kernel = "linear", ranges = list(cost = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100)),
                   scale=FALSE)
summary(svm_housing_linear)

Getting the Hyperplane

We can also look at the weights (predictor line coefficients) within the model as follows

w <- t(new_tune_housing_linear$coefs) %*% new_tune_housing_linear$SV
w
##            age  hhincome  bedrooms    mar_st6     mar_st4   mar_st3   mar_st1
## [1,] 0.3316987 0.2892621 0.9069701 -0.2858485 -0.02235735 -0.288961 0.2243024
##        mar_st5   mar_st2  education numOfPeople_hh married_SpousePresent1
## [1,] 0.1058913 0.2669732 0.05087782     -0.1504691              0.2243024
##      married_SpouseAbsent1 isseparated1   Divorced1 isWidowed1 issingle0
## [1,]             0.2669732    -0.288961 -0.02235735  0.1058913 0.2858485
abs_w <- abs(w)

largest_indices <- order(abs_w, decreasing = TRUE)[1:2]

# Get the two largest weights
weights <- w[largest_indices]
weights
## [1] 0.9069701 0.3316987

From the weights, it shows that bedrooms and age are the strongest predictors for housing.

# pick the x and y coefficients
bx = w[1] # age
by = w[3] # bedrooms 
b0 = new_tune_housing_linear$rho # equivalent to beta_0 in e1071 implementation

# plot
base = ggplot(data=final_housing_data, mapping= aes(x = bedrooms, y = age)) 
base + geom_point(aes(color=ownership)) +
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=b0/by, color='black') +
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=(b0+1)/by, color='gray') + 
  geom_abline(slope=-bx/by, intercept=(b0-1)/by, color='gray') + 
  geom_point(data=data.frame(new_tune_housing_linear$SV), mapping = aes(x =bedrooms, y = age), shape=4, size=5)

plot(new_tune_housing_linear,final_housing_data, hhincome ~ bedrooms, pch = 19,
     xlab = "Bedrooms", ylab = "Household Income",
     main = "Relationship between bedrooms and Household Income")

# Check column names in final_housing_data
names(final_housing_data)
##  [1] "age"                   "hhincome"              "bedrooms"             
##  [4] "mar_st"                "education"             "ownership"            
##  [7] "numOfPeople_hh"        "married_SpousePresent" "married_SpouseAbsent" 
## [10] "isseparated"           "Divorced"              "isWidowed"            
## [13] "issingle"
plot(new_tune_housing_linear,final_housing_data, hhincome ~ education, pch = 19,
